WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.640
EUROPEAN STOCK EXCHANGES

00:00:06.999 --> 00:00:12.999
There is no doubt that the
Zagreb Stock Exchange developed

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:21.480
in line with the stock exchanges
in Europe and around the world.

00:00:21.999 --> 00:00:27.999
Its origins go back to ancient
times or the Hanseatic era.

00:00:27.999 --> 00:00:32.999
The first exchange
was founded in Amsterdam.

00:00:32.999 --> 00:00:38.960
This had no impact on Croatia.

00:00:38.999 --> 00:00:43.999
Our first exchange
emerged in Rijeka in 1781.

00:00:43.999 --> 00:00:54.960
It traded in sugar as this was the
only commodity produced in Rijeka.

00:00:54.999 --> 00:00:58.800
Rijeka was actually
the main sugar supplier

00:00:58.999 --> 00:01:02.999
for the Habsburg Monarchy
and the Ottoman Empire.

00:01:02.999 --> 00:01:12.999
There is a beautiful hall in Rijeka
adorned with breathtaking paintings

00:01:12.999 --> 00:01:18.999
whose purpose was to make
sugar traders feel better.

00:01:18.999 --> 00:01:21.999
Luka Sorkočević
took over this idea

00:01:21.999 --> 00:01:24.999
and had a similar hall
built in Rijeka Dubrovačka

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.999
where Rijeka had a subsidiary
for the Ottoman Empire.

00:01:31.999 --> 00:01:40.999
By the end of the 18th century, all
nation-states had their exchanges.

00:01:40.999 --> 00:01:49.480
The oldest one is
the London Exchange,

00:01:49.999 --> 00:01:53.999
which dates back to 1560.
The Paris Exchange

00:01:53.999 --> 00:02:00.160
was founded in 1563.
At the end of the 18th century,

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:04.999
it became clear that the exchanges
should be modernised.

00:02:04.999 --> 00:02:08.999
For this purpose, Napoleon adopted
the Code de Commerce,

00:02:08.999 --> 00:02:11.000
a commerce act,

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:16.800
on the basis of which the Paris
Stock Exchange was to be built.

00:02:16.999 --> 00:02:20.999
Construction began
in 1809, and ended in 1828.

00:02:20.999 --> 00:02:26.480
As social changes took hold in
the mid 19th century, Europe

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:29.999
saw the emergence
of the Vienna Stock Exchange

00:02:29.999 --> 00:02:34.999
and that of Budapest in 1868.

00:02:34.999 --> 00:02:42.800
It resulted from the need to regulate
the foreign exchange market

00:02:42.999 --> 00:02:45.999
and the standardised
commodities trade

00:02:45.999 --> 00:02:52.999
as well as to facilitate trade on
the basis of commercial samples.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.999
This, of course, had an
impact on our domestic trade

00:02:57.999 --> 00:03:02.999
but around 1900
there was a huge problem

00:03:02.999 --> 00:03:04.999
arising from the effort

00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:09.999
to organise the foreign exchange
and commodities trade in Zagreb

00:03:09.999 --> 00:03:11.999
in the same manner.

00:03:11.999 --> 00:03:17.999
THE DEVELOPMENT OF
THE ZAGREB STOCK EXCHANGE

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:23.800
Count Khuen
Hedervary's era showed

00:03:23.999 --> 00:03:31.999
that Croatia could no longer
exist as some sort of a colony.

00:03:31.999 --> 00:03:34.999
In 1903 a new era was dawning,

00:03:34.999 --> 00:03:39.999
largely thanks to the tradesmen
who lived in Zagreb

00:03:39.999 --> 00:03:45.999
and had chosen
Zagreb as their business centre.

00:03:45.999 --> 00:03:50.999
The Zagreb Trading House
was founded in 1900

00:03:50.999 --> 00:03:54.800
and the Tradesmen
Association in 1904

00:03:54.999 --> 00:03:59.999
at the Grand Café on
today's Ban Jelačić Square.

00:03:59.999 --> 00:04:05.999
In 1907, the Commodities
and Stocks Section

00:04:05.999 --> 00:04:09.999
was established within
the Trading House.

00:04:09.999 --> 00:04:12.999
Even then it was
called the stock exchange,

00:04:12.999 --> 00:04:17.999
but if you look at the documents,
you will find it under the name of

00:04:17.999 --> 00:04:21.999
the Commodities
and Stocks Section.

00:04:21.999 --> 00:04:25.999
The scope of the stock exchange
and the Section was the same.

00:04:25.999 --> 00:04:27.999
The Section was very important

00:04:27.999 --> 00:04:31.999
as it enabled an accelerated
commodities trade.

00:04:31.999 --> 00:04:38.160
Gjuro Deželić, who
retired in 1906, said

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:42.999
that the institution was of key
importance for the Croatian people

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:47.000
and that he did not
understand why state officials

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:53.999
and city representatives
did not attend its opening.

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:56.999
Regardless of that,
the Section began operations.

00:04:56.999 --> 00:05:03.999
In 1913, it moved to today's
European House in Jurišić Street,

00:05:03.999 --> 00:05:11.640
where it remained until 1927.

00:05:11.999 --> 00:05:15.999
However, the Stock Exchange
operated with interruptions.

00:05:15.999 --> 00:05:24.640
It was closed in 1914 by World War I,
as all monopolised goods,

00:05:24.999 --> 00:05:29.999
including grain, meat, etc., were
traded with through state sections

00:05:29.999 --> 00:05:32.999
for the purpose of war commerce

00:05:32.999 --> 00:05:37.999
and whatever else a particular
country deemed necessary.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:49.999
When the strict war commerce
began to lose its grip in 1917

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:56.999
after Emperor Franz Josef's
death, the Tradesmen Association

00:05:56.999 --> 00:06:03.999
renewed the Section
on 4 January 1918,

00:06:03.999 --> 00:06:09.999
but now under a new name -
the Stock Exchange.

00:06:09.999 --> 00:06:15.999
The Stock Exchange remained
in operation even at the end of 1918,

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:21.999
during the State of Slovenes,
Croats and Serbs

00:06:21.999 --> 00:06:26.320
that lasted only 45 days.

00:06:26.999 --> 00:06:33.960
This can be attributed to Dr Ðuro
Šurmin, a university professor

00:06:33.999 --> 00:06:38.999
and the National Council's
Trade and Industry Commissioner.

00:06:38.999 --> 00:06:47.999
On 4 December 1918 he organised
a meeting to choose members

00:06:47.999 --> 00:06:55.000
for the Stock Exchange Council
and to adopt the rulebook

00:06:55.480 --> 00:07:02.999
as he believed that the new state,
founded on 1 December,

00:07:02.999 --> 00:07:09.999
would realise the importance of
Zagreb and its stock exchange.

00:07:09.999 --> 00:07:13.999
He saw its potential to help the
state overcome the post-war crisis

00:07:13.999 --> 00:07:18.999
and start actively participating in
Europe's commercial operations.

00:07:18.999 --> 00:07:24.999
In 1918, the Stock Exchange
was restored

00:07:24.999 --> 00:07:29.999
with both its foreign exchange and
commodities departments operating

00:07:29.999 --> 00:07:34.999
and the Exchange did indeed
become a powerful centre

00:07:34.999 --> 00:07:38.999
which helped the
newly founded state,

00:07:38.999 --> 00:07:46.999
the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and
Slovenes, to overcome the crisis.

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:51.800
Even though the Stock Exchange
operated according to the rules,

00:07:51.999 --> 00:07:56.999
and even though Šurmin thought
there could be two state centres,

00:07:56.999 --> 00:08:01.999
one political - Belgrade,
and one commercial - Zagreb,

00:08:01.999 --> 00:08:03.999
this did not happen

00:08:03.999 --> 00:08:12.480
as Belgrade put all its efforts
into moving commerce there.

00:08:12.999 --> 00:08:19.999
By 1923 this slowed
down its activities

00:08:19.999 --> 00:08:28.999
even though a provision validated
the Zagreb Stock Exchange,

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:39.999
since then, the year 1919
is taken as its founding year.

00:08:39.999 --> 00:08:44.320
We know, however,
that it was founded in 1907

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:47.999
regardless of all its ups and downs.

00:08:47.999 --> 00:08:50.999
It is interesting to analyse

00:08:50.999 --> 00:08:56.999
how Belgrade slowly took
over the Zagreb Stock Exchange.

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:05.999
When the kruna was substituted
by the dinar, at a ratio of 4 to 1,

00:09:05.999 --> 00:09:10.640
Zagreb's business community
was not greatly affected

00:09:10.999 --> 00:09:13.160
as these were
highly skilled traders

00:09:13.480 --> 00:09:18.480
who fitted well into
Europe's monetary system.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:23.999
But when Milan Stojadinović
became the Minister of Finance,

00:09:23.999 --> 00:09:31.320
the Zagreb Stock Exchange
was no longer allowed

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:37.999
foreign exchange trade.
Direct commodities trade,

00:09:37.999 --> 00:09:42.160
both mass and standardised,
was blocked.

00:09:42.480 --> 00:09:46.999
Thus the commercial centre
began moving to Belgrade.

00:09:46.999 --> 00:09:50.999
However, in 1921,

00:09:51.160 --> 00:09:56.999
when the Zagreb Stock Exchange
was the only stock exchange here

00:09:56.999 --> 00:10:00.999
that traded with Europe, a
binding decision was made

00:10:00.999 --> 00:10:04.999
to build a special palace
for the Zagreb Stock Exchange.

00:10:04.999 --> 00:10:08.999
This had actually already
been stipulated at the meeting

00:10:08.999 --> 00:10:15.999
on 4 December 1918 when
Šurmin made such a proposal.

00:10:15.999 --> 00:10:20.480
Designs were made in 1921,

00:10:20.999 --> 00:10:28.999
and thanks to the efforts of
Croatian and Slavonian traders,

00:10:28.999 --> 00:10:35.999
this grand edifice, the Zagreb Stock
Exchange Palace, was built in 1927.

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:39.800
It was built in marble

00:10:39.999 --> 00:10:44.999
and had elements of the state-of
-the-art architecture of that period.

00:10:44.999 --> 00:10:49.999
However, all this was
done with an aim.

00:10:49.999 --> 00:10:55.999
The plan was to build a similar
palace across the street

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.640
but it was only built ten years later.

00:10:59.999 --> 00:11:06.999
It was supposed to
be an entrance to Zagreb's City,

00:11:06.999 --> 00:11:12.999
since the modern Zagreb
was to be built to the south-east,

00:11:12.999 --> 00:11:16.999
as indeed happened.

00:11:16.999 --> 00:11:25.999
The palace enabled Zagreb's
and Croatia's businessmen

00:11:25.999 --> 00:11:33.640
to remain a significant
factor in the Croatian economy.

00:11:33.999 --> 00:11:35.999
THE GREAT DEPRESSION

00:11:35.999 --> 00:11:39.999
AND THE DISCONTINUATION
OF THE STOCK EXCHANGE

00:11:39.999 --> 00:11:46.999
The Great Depression was
not felt in the country in 1929,

00:11:46.999 --> 00:11:49.320
but there was a political crisis then.

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:54.999
The economic crisis started
only in the autumn of 1931,

00:11:54.999 --> 00:11:58.999
with the collapse of the
First Croatian Savings Bank.

00:11:58.999 --> 00:12:03.999
Commissioners were appointed to
head all the monetary institutions,

00:12:03.999 --> 00:12:06.999
including the
Zagreb Stock Exchange.

00:12:06.999 --> 00:12:13.999
The commissioners included
Radomir Zec and Dušan Plavšić.

00:12:13.999 --> 00:12:23.999
They worked as Belgrade dictated.
The Stock Exchange kept operating

00:12:23.999 --> 00:12:25.999
but its activities were reduced.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.999
It was not allowed
to trade in foreign exchange,

00:12:29.320 --> 00:12:32.999
but it helped the country
get out of the crisis

00:12:32.999 --> 00:12:36.999
as the employees
spoke German well,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:42.999
and thus helped Yugoslavia enter
trading agreements with Germany.

00:12:42.999 --> 00:12:45.999
This happened in 1934

00:12:45.999 --> 00:12:52.999
when the Third Reich started
purchasing all the market surpluses

00:12:52.999 --> 00:12:55.999
produced in Yugoslavia.

00:12:55.999 --> 00:12:59.999
It was crucial to do business
through the Zagreb Stock Exchange

00:12:59.999 --> 00:13:02.999
as it had a central position with
regard to Bosnia and Herzegovina

00:13:02.999 --> 00:13:08.999
and its mineral resources, grain
and cattle. All this prevented

00:13:08.999 --> 00:13:14.999
the crisis from having
a major impact on Zagreb.

00:13:14.999 --> 00:13:17.999
The country managed to
pull through in 1932,

00:13:17.999 --> 00:13:21.999
with the help of construction work
and increased export,

00:13:21.999 --> 00:13:26.999
which could not have developed
without the participation of Zagreb.

00:13:26.999 --> 00:13:30.999
This continued in the Autonomous
Banovina of Croatia as well.

00:13:30.999 --> 00:13:34.999
Stock Exchange presidents changed,

00:13:35.160 --> 00:13:38.999
but all of them
were noted businessmen.

00:13:38.999 --> 00:13:42.999
Many of whom
became ministers in Belgrade,

00:13:42.999 --> 00:13:45.480
and cooperated well with Serbs

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:48.999
but also contributed to the
development of Croatian economy,

00:13:48.999 --> 00:13:52.999
which was by no means crushed
in the period between the wars.

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:56.999
It was crushed, however,
by World War II

00:13:56.999 --> 00:14:02.999
and the emergence
of war commerce.

00:14:02.999 --> 00:14:08.800
All valuable
goods went to the Third Reich,

00:14:08.999 --> 00:14:13.320
which underpriced
everything it bought

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:17.999
and overpriced everything it sold,
for instance technical goods,

00:14:17.999 --> 00:14:24.999
so there was always a huge trade
gap between Croatia and Germany.

00:14:24.999 --> 00:14:28.999
Croatia was constantly in debt.

00:14:28.999 --> 00:14:42.999
In 1945, the activities
of all banks came to a halt

00:14:42.999 --> 00:14:49.999
and the Stock Exchange
was badly affected by this.

00:14:50.999 --> 00:14:54.999
The whole ground-floor was leased out

00:14:55.320 --> 00:15:01.999
since the Stock Exchange
no longer had many employees,

00:15:01.999 --> 00:15:08.999
as Belgrade had played it. During
the Independent State of Croatia,

00:15:08.999 --> 00:15:16.999
the Stock Exchange worked with
the Nazis. This ended in 1945,

00:15:16.999 --> 00:15:21.999
when the Exchange was pronounced
a speculative institution

00:15:21.999 --> 00:15:28.999
and its archives were
destroyed so we cannot

00:15:28.999 --> 00:15:35.960
reconstruct its business
on the basis of exact numbers.

00:15:35.999 --> 00:15:41.160
We know that balance sheets are
rarely made known to the public,

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:43.999
especially in the case
of the stock exchange.

00:15:43.999 --> 00:15:49.960
There were many
secret transactions

00:15:49.999 --> 00:15:53.160
and we have only
partial information.

00:15:53.640 --> 00:15:59.999
I do know, however, that in 1943,
trade with the Third Reich

00:15:59.999 --> 00:16:07.480
amounted to 6 billion kuna,
and trade with Rome to 711 million.

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:14.999
So a huge amount of money was
going through the Stock Exchange

00:16:14.999 --> 00:16:23.999
to different companies. In 1945
the premises were reallocated

00:16:23.999 --> 00:16:29.999
and that was the
end of the Stock Exchange.

00:16:30.999 --> 00:16:34.640
The library of the Croatian Chamber
of Trades and Craft still exists,

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:37.999
but has been kept
in the underground vaults

00:16:37.999 --> 00:16:42.800
of the National Library.
To open them would be helpful

00:16:42.999 --> 00:16:51.999
and would shed light on the history
of Croatian economic institutions.

00:16:52.800 --> 00:17:00.999
I have no idea why it is still closed
and has been so since 1946.

00:17:00.999 --> 00:17:02.999
However, that archive
concerns only the Chamber

00:17:02.999 --> 00:17:05.999
and not the Stock Exchange

00:17:05.999 --> 00:17:07.999
whose archives were
almost completely destroyed.

